 ## ABOUT DATA TYPE IN GOLAN 

 ***In Go (Golang), data types are organized into four main categories based on how they store and manage data. 
1. Basic Types (Primitive Types)
These are the fundamental building blocks used to represent simple values: 
Numbers:
Integers: Includes signed (int, int8, int16, int32, int64) and unsigned (uint, uint8, uint16, uint32, uint64, uintptr).
Floating-Point: Used for decimals (float32, float64).
Complex Numbers: Used for mathematical computations with real and imaginary parts (complex64, complex128).
Booleans: The bool type, which can only be true or false.
Strings: Immutable sequences of characters (UTF-8 encoded). 
Medium
Medium
 +5
2. Aggregate Types
These types combine multiple values into a single entity:
Arrays: Fixed-size collections of elements of the same type.
Structs: Collections of fields that can store different data types under one name. 
Medium
Medium
 +2
3. Reference Types
These types store a reference (pointer) to the actual data, meaning modifications often affect the original source: 
Slices: Dynamically-sized views into arrays.
Maps: Key-value pairs (hash tables).
Pointers: Variables that store the memory address of another value.
Channels: Used for communication and synchronization between goroutines.
Functions: In Go, functions are first-class citizens and can be assigned to variables. 
Medium
Medium
 +5
4. Interface Type
Interfaces: Define a set of method signatures. A variable of an interface type can hold any value that implements those methods, providing polymorphism in Go. 
